    {
      "number": 13,
      "id": "I_kwDONMXNnM6gSByC",
      "title": "use IP_PMTUDISC_PROBE instead of IP_PMTUDISC_DO on Linux",
      "url": "https://github.com/marten-seemann/draft-seemann-tsvwg-udp-fragmentation/issues/13",
      "state": "OPEN",
      "author": "marten-seemann",
      "authorAssociation": "OWNER",
      "assignees": [],
      "labels": [],
      "body": "And explain the difference between the two.",
      "createdAt": "2024-11-25T04:41:45Z",
      "updatedAt": "2024-11-29T10:47:27Z",
      "closedAt": null,
      "comments": [
        {
          "author": "mxinden",
          "authorAssociation": "NONE",
          "body": "Maybe stating the obvious, also `IPV6_MTU_DISCOVER` `IPV6_PMTUDISC_PROBE`.\r\n\r\nIn addition, I found the following in `quinn-udp`:\r\n\r\n``` rust\r\n            // Linux's IP_PMTUDISC_PROBE allows us to operate under interface MTU rather than the\r\n            // kernel's path MTU guess, but actually disabling fragmentation requires this too. See\r\n            // __ip6_append_data in ip6_output.c.\r\n            // Set `may_fragment` to `true` if this option is not supported on the platform.\r\n            may_fragment |=\r\n                !set_socket_option_supported(&*io, libc::IPPROTO_IPV6, IPV6_DONTFRAG, OPTION_ON)?;\r\n```\r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/quinn-rs/quinn/blob/e318cc4a80436fd9fa19c02886d682c49efca185/quinn-udp/src/unix.rs#L178-L183\r\n\r\n@marten-seemann based on your experience with quic-go, is the above obsolete?",
          "createdAt": "2024-11-29T10:47:26Z",
          "updatedAt": "2024-11-29T10:47:26Z"
        }
      ]
    }
